{This book is for those who want to beat the King's Indian and Grünfeld
Defences without studying for years. My goal is to offer sound but unexplored
lines. --- Take the King's Indian first - what sort of players are our foes?
--- King's Indian players love to build up prolonged attacks behind their wall
of pawns. For example, no matter what new lines White throws at them in the
Mar del Plata variation, the Black players are happy: White might win the
queenside, but if the sable forces break through, the white king dies.} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 g6 {. I have no interest in this extremely fashionable line, for two
reasons. One, I have no desire to see my king get attacked - I'd rather do the
attacking! Two, the amount of theory in the Mar del Plata has long passed the
"well analyzed" point and has now become "completely absurd"! Only a computer
or a twenty year old raised with a computer wired into his brain can deal with
the near infinite number of "book" variations. --- Let's take a random example.
Here is the great Garry Kasparov defeating a world class player, Boris Gelfand,
on the black side of the infamous variation (see the following game).} *

