{In this book I'm offering two main variations of the Four Pawns Attack as the
best practical way for the creative, attacking player to defeat the King's
Indian. --- My number one, "win at all costs" line is what I will call the
Martz Variation, after the American IM who played it with great success
throughout his career. In this line White plays for a Maróczy Bind set-up that
gives him space and attacking chances. Even more important, Black will be too
busy defending to think of attacking you! --- Let's see what the Big Database
has to say about this line. Taking one of the games that will be featured in
this book, we have my win as White against GM George Grigore of Romania.} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. f4 c5 7. Nf3 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9.
Be3 Qb6 10. Nc2 Qa5 11. O-O Nd7 12. Bd2 Qb6+ 13. Kh1 Nc5 14. b4 Bxc3 15. bxc5
Qa5 16. Bxc3 Qxc3 17. cxd6 exd6 18. Rf3 Qf6 19. Ne3 Qd4 20. Qf1 Qxe4 21. f5
Bxf5 22. Nxf5 gxf5 23. Bd3 Qe7 24. Bxf5 Ne5 25. Re1 h6 26. Re4 Kh8 27. Rh3 Kg7
28. Rg3+ Kh8 29. Qc1 Qf6 30. Rf4 Rg8 31. Bh7 Qe6 32. Bxg8 Rxg8 33. Rh4 Rg6 34.
Rxg6 Nxg6 35. Rxh6+ Kg7 36. Rh3 Qe2 37. Rb3 Qe7 38. h3 b6 39. Rg3 Kg8 40. Qf1
Kg7 41. Qa1+ Kg8 42. Rg4 Qe6 43. Qd4 Kf8 44. Re4 Ne5 45. Qd5 Qf6 46. Re1 Kg7
47. Rd1 Qf5 48. Qxd6 f6 49. c5 bxc5 50. Qxc5 Kg6 51. Qxa7 Nd3 52. Kg1 Qe4 53.
Rf1 Nf4 54. Qf2 Ne2+ 55. Kh2 Qe5+ 56. g3 Nc3 57. Qf4 Qe6 58. a3 f5 59. g4 {.
After eight moves, which establishes the Martz Variation, the Big Database
finds only 270 games - now this is a lot more manageable than 15,783! And by
move 20, the game has entered completely uncharted realms (I offer an original
pawn sacrifice at this point) and there is no such thing as "theory", no other
games in the database, just two competitors playing chess, not showing off
their memory or computer programs! --- Now let's step back into the past,
before the infernal machine was invented, and revisit some great games from
perhaps the most famous international tournament of all time, New York 1924.
--- Alexander Alekhine, three years away from dethroning Capablanca and
becoming the fourth World Champion, fearlessly ventured the Four Pawns Attack
in three crucial games against very strong opposition: Frank Marshall, F.D.Yates, and Edward Lasker. He scored 2-1, a win against Yates and two draws,
which is a good percentage score, but there is a lot more to learn from these
games than result percentages. --- If we look more deeply at these games, we
see that, based on how he came out of the opening, Alekhine should have scored
3-0! There is no doubt that the future World Champion had a decisive advantage
by move 20 in all three games, as the following analysis will show. --- So
that's quite good for our opening, yes?} (59. -- {But let's look a little
further still. In the two drawn games, I will demonstrate that Alekhine went
from having a crushing position out of the opening to dead lost endings! Yes,
both Marshall and Edward Lasker missed absolutely forced wins! The half points
were saved only by Alekhine's gutsy defence, his incredible belief in his own
position, and yes, his opponents' blunders. --- Now what should we think of
the opening? The result could just as easily have been 1-2 (!), surely not so
good for White. --- The answer is simply this: the Four Pawns Attack is a
risky opening. By advancing all four of his most central pawns, White burns
his own bridges by move five! Pawns can't move backward! The direct assault
from the pawn phalanx means that White can blow his opponent away in twenty
moves; yet this same assault leaves weaknesses in the White position, which
means that the slightest mistake (as even such a great player as Alekhine
might make) can completely reverse the evaluation of the position. --- This is
the point where you, the prospective reader, should now either run to the cash
register or run away in terror!}) (59. -- {I promise you a very sharp, still
quite unexplored line, by which you may "Beat the King's Indian". However, I
do not promise you a free ride - by "signing on" to the Four Pawns Attack, you
are taking a chance, committing your whole army even before development. ---
You're taking a risk. --- If you play it right, you will be amazed at how many
quick victories you score. --- But you might also suffer a painful endgame
loss or two - or then again, you might be like Alekhine, and even when your
attack fails, you'll still save the ending! --- The most important thing is
that White attacks fiercely by move six. A few more moves and Black can be
overwhelmed. --- Or he had better be overwhelmed, but just remember, fortune
favours the brave! --- Alekhine got ready to be World Champion by risking all
in the highest profile encounters. --- (Just a thought here, can you imagine
Kramnik playing the Four Pawns Attack at Linares??) --- Now let's see Alekhine
take his chances (see the following game).}) 1-0

