analogous Marshall game the second player had the threat to conquer d4,} ({but
here the same manoeuvre fails tactically:} 7... e5 8. fxe5 dxe5 9. d5 Nd4 10.
Nxd4 exd4 11. Qxd4 {and now} Nxe4 $4 {fails as the e-file is not open,} ({but
if instead} 11... Ng4 12. Qd3 Qh4+ 13. Qg3 {and Black has no real compensation
for the pawn.})) 8. Be3 e5 {Black accomplishes this central counter, but what
did he really get out of it? The knight on d7 is misplaced, blocking the
c8-bishop, while the knight on c6 will soon be hit as White gains space with
tempo.} 9. fxe5 dxe5 10. d5 Ncb8 11. c5 {Alekhine bluntly states that White's
position is already "won from a strategical point of view." The computer
agrees, giving White a plus of over 1 point, so it's as if White were already
a clear pawn up. --- Why these overwhelmingly one-sided evaluations? Just look
at the position! --- White has, first and foremost, a huge advantage in the
centre, in that the mobile d- and c-pawns (both already on the fifth rank!)
dominate that sector of the board. Meanwhile Black has no, I mean zero
queenside development. --- White's half-open f-file is clearly more useful
than Black's half-open d-file: the former can easily be part of an attack
involving such natural moves as 0-0, Bc4, and d5-d6, while one sees no
prospects for Black on the d-file, seeing as he only controls two squares of
it! --- So Alekhine's evaluation is correct: White has a won game... but wait!
It's only move eleven! Black is a strong player, the equivalent today of a
solid mid-range GM. How can he be busted so fast? --- The answer lies, once
again, in the sharpness of this opening. Black was too slow finding
counterplay - his two knight manoeuvre just lost time and space - and White's
pawns were even so early ready to roll forward. --- This is the kind of crush
that makes this opening so much fun to play!} a5 12. O-O Na6 13. Na4 Qe7 14.
Rc1 h6 {One can't call this move a blunder: Black's position is so horrible
that anything would lose.} ({For example, had Black avoided the skewer seen in
the game with} 14... Re8 {, White would have set up the crushing f-file attack
mentioned in the note above with} 15. d6 cxd6 16. cxd6 Qd8 17. Bc4 {and
White's pressure is decisive.}) 15. Bxa6 {Alekhine alertly picks up the
exchange with this tactic,} ({but} 15. d6 cxd6 16. cxd6 Qd8 17. Bc4 {as above
is also good, with a huge positional advantage.}) 15... Rxa6 16. c6 bxc6 17.
dxc6 Nb8 18. Bc5 Qe8 19. Bxf8 Bxf8 20. Nc3 Rxc6 21. Nd5 {White is winning. The
knight on d5 dominates the board, while Black has only a dubious and soon lost
queenside pawn for the exchange. Alekhine handles the technical part
efficiently.} Rd6 22. Rxc7 Na6 23. Rc3 Nb4 24. Nxe5 $1 {Tactical alertness
once again! Black might have saved himself some trouble and resigned now - the
rest needs no comment.} Ba6 25. Nc4 Bxc4 26. Rxc4 Qe5 27. Qf3 f5 28. Nxb4 axb4
29. exf5 Rf6 30. Qe4 Bc5+ 31. Kh1 Rxf5 32. Rxf5 {. The moral of this game is
clear: the unprepared Black player can be busted by move eleven in the Four
Pawns Attack!} 1-0

