here too, because Edward Lasker, like Marshall, fails to find the winning
tactic.} 39. Ra7 Nd4+ $4 ({The simple} 39... Bc5 $1 40. Ra4 (40. Rxa2 Rf2+ {
skewers and wins}) 40... Bd4 {forces resignation - but the good player is
lucky again! Now Alekhine finally calms down and fights successfully to draw.})
40. Kd3 Rf3+ 41. Ke4 Rf1 42. Bb2 Nxc6 43. Rxa2 Rf4+ 44. Ke3 Bc5+ 45. Ke2 Rf2+
46. Ke1 Rxh2 47. Be4 Nd4 48. Bxd4 Bb4+ 49. Kf1 Rxa2 50. Bd5+ Kf8 51. Bxa2 exd4
52. Bb1 Kg7 53. Kg2 {. Conclusion: There can be no better introduction to the
pluses and minuses of the Four Pawns Attack than these three games. --- The
power of the opening can be seen by the fact that Alekhine reached a winning
position by move 20 in all three games (and he was winning by move eleven
against Yates!). --- The risk factor can be seen with equal clarity. By
throwing all his centre pawns forward in the opening, White leaves himself no
way to retreat, making any mistake twice as dangerous. --- The opening
literally requires White to be ruthlessly accurate, or his dominant centre and
middlegame attack could meltdown into a lost ending! --- Amusingly enough, two
World Champions who were renowned for their solid play - Capablanca and
Petrosian - both ventured the Four Pawns Attack (Game 4 for Capa, Game 21 for
Petrosian) and in each case the champion won decisively in 24 moves! Did this
encourage Jose and Tigran to play this opening on a regular basis? No!
Undoubtedly shocked by the level of risk they had assumed, despite their quick
successes, neither champion ever dared play this wild attack again! --- But if
you are ready to take some chances, turn the page!} 1/2-1/2

