{How to beat the King's Indian?} 1. -- {I am offering two recipes.} ({First,
the Martz Variation, which I consider objectively strongest. The moves to
reach the basic tabiya are:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. -- (5.
Be2 O-O 6. f4 c5 7. Nf3 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9. Be3 {.}) ({. The second, the Liz
Variation, is reached after} 5. f4 O-O 6. Nf3 c5 7. d5 e6 8. Be2 exd5 9. exd5 {
. This is slightly quieter and safer than the Martz, but also gives good
winning chances. This will be covered in Chapters 3 and 4, and I will discuss
the ideas of this variation in the introduction to Chapter 3.}) ({. You will
notice I completely reject the transposition to the Benoni that could occur in
either line after} 5. Be2 O-O 6. f4 c5 7. d5 e6 8. Nf3 exd5 9. cxd5 {. There
are two reasons for this: One, I simply cannot stand these booked-up
variations. How many games does the above line have in the Big Database? 2822!
The very number makes my head hurt, and what hurts more is that some twelve
year old I might play probably has every game memorized! --- My second reason
is a pure chess analysis one: I think that Black can objectively equalize in
that Benoni line with the best counter,} Bg4 {, when White scores less than
50% and I can't find any particular improvement - and if I really wanted to
look for one, I'd have to find it out around move 25, which is far too absurd
for me! I prefer a less booked-up line that offers good winning chances! --- I
call the Martz Variation, the subject of Chapters 1 and 2 of this book, after
the American IM William Martz who played it with success throughout his career.
I witnessed one of his upsets: at Lone Pine in the 70s, Martz had White
against Petrosian. He whipped out his variation, and Petrosian immediately
smelled a very large rat - and offered a draw on, as I recall, either move 10
or 11! Martz politely accepted the ex-World Champion's offer. Given the big
rating difference between them a draw was a success for Martz, but I wonder if
perhaps later he regretted not playing on?} (9... --))) ({What sort of
position scared Petrosian so much that he had to offer an IM a draw in the
opening? To repeat the opening moves, the basic tabiya is reached after:} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. f4 c5 7. Nf3 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9.
Be3 {White has a sort of super Maróczy Bind, with the regular bind (pawns at
c4 and e4, knight at d4) accentuated by the pawn at f4, which adds attacking
chances to the normal Maróczy squeeze. --- It's important to note that many
other openings that can reach Maróczy positions can transpose to the above
variation. Consider if we add a move for each colour to the above variation:}
Bd7 10. O-O {.}) ({We then reach a position from Game 4, which started out as
a Sicilian Accelerated Dragon:} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5.
Be3 Bg7 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. Be2 Bd7 9. O-O O-O 10. f4 {.}) ({Game 5 uses an
English or Réti move order:} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 c5 5. d4 cxd4
6. Nxd4 d6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 9. Be3 {and we're back to the Martz! It's
good to know these tricky transpositions, which are also good for confusing
your opponent! --- But back to the main ideas: As I said above, the Martz
combines positional squeeze with attacking potential. The most popular defence
is} Bd7 {seen in Games 4, 5 and 6. Black simply develops and dares White to do
his worst - unfortunately for Black, that "worst" often turns out to be a
fatal attack on the black king! See Game 6 for a relentless example of direct
assault!} ({An opposite defensive strategy is seen in Games 7-10. There Black
tries to immediately exchange pieces with bishop or knight to g4. The} 9... Bg4
{line forces off a large number of pieces, including the queens, though the
ending is still difficult for Black.}) ({Fischer liked the} 9... Ng4 {line,
but improvements for White have been found. --- Less popular defences - which
are often more dangerous for Black - are dealt with in Games 11-15. One should
note that even small inaccuracies by Black can be severely punished, as in
Game 11, Taylor-Hermansen.})) *

