1. e4 {Before we begin, and confuse everyone with the first game of the main
book starting with 1 e4 (wasn't this a book for 1 d4 players?), let me give a
note on move order. As I mentioned in the introduction, the Four Pawns Attack
of the King's Indian can arise from the Accelerated Dragon, and also from
English/Réti systems. --- But what if we actually start off with the d-pawn?
There is a particular move order I recommend to reach the Martz Variation, and
a different one I recommend to reach the Liz Variation.} ({First things first:
I think the best Martz (from 1 d4) goes as follows:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 ({I recommend} 5. f4 {here to reach the Liz Variation, see
the intro to Chapter 3 for the explanation}) 5... O-O 6. f4 c5 7. Nf3 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Nc6 9. Be3 {. Notice that White plays 5 Be2, and only then 6 f4. The
reasons are twofold: First, White looks to see where Black's king lives: if he
castles (by far the most popular move) we know where we can mate him!}) ({
Second, if he plays} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 c5 {, we
play} 6. Nf3 {, and reach the variation as follows:} cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nc6 8. Be3
O-O 9. f4 {.}) ({This avoids the pitfall that could occur after} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f4 c5 $5 6. Nf3 $6 (6. d5 {is best, but that is
not a Martz!}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nc6 8. Be3 Ng4 {and Black has the initiative;
see Game 15, Taylor-Peters, for further notes.}) 1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4
4. Nxd4 g6 5. Be3 Bg7 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. Be2 Bd7 9. O-O O-O 10. f4 {The
Martz Variation of the King's Indian Defence has been reached. (Or if you must
follow your codes, B38 has become E79!)} Ng4 {This common Sicilian diversion,
aimed at the d4-square, is by no means always sound versus the Four Pawns
Attack. In this case it fails miserably as Black's queen's bishop has already
moved once, and so Black is a tempo down on the main ...Ng4 lines.} ({Equally
faulty is} 10... Bg4 11. Nxc6 Bxe2 12. Nxe7+ Qxe7 13. Qxe2 Nxe4 14. Nd5 Qd7 15.
f5 $1 {with a big attack for White.}) ({For the modern} 10... Nxd4 {and other
alternatives, see the next two games. (There is of course the Petrosian
alternative - offer a draw! - but this does not work for everyone.)}) 11. Bxg4
Bxg4 ({The other capture is no better:} 11... Bxd4 12. Bxd4 Bxg4 13. Qxg4 Nxd4
14. Qd1 {reaches the exact same position as Pomar-Geller, Game 10 (which
already favours White), with the very useful extra tempo 0-0 gained because
Black's bishop took two steps to get to g4.}) 12. Nxc6 Qd7 ({Still worse is} 
12... Bxd1 13. Nxd8 Bc2 14. Nxb7 Rab8 15. Rf2 {and White emerges a clean piece
up.}) 13. Nxe7+ {Capablanca refutes smoothly as always. This desperado wins a
clear pawn - Capa could even go for a second pawn on the next move at the cost
of time (14 Ng6+) but remains true to himself and wins cleanly and simply.} Kh8
14. Qd3 Qxe7 15. Nd5 Qd7 16. f5 $1 {A thrust well known to all Bird's Opening
players, and quite common in the Four Pawns Attack: White crosses the central
meridian with the intrepid f-pawn and begins a kingside attack, in this case
also threatening to trap the g4-bishop.} gxf5 ({White wins prettily after the
pawn snatch} 16... Bxb2 {with} 17. Bd4+ Bxd4+ 18. Qxd4+ f6 19. fxg6 hxg6 20.
Nxf6 Qg7 21. e5 Bh5 (21... dxe5 22. Qxg4 {snags a piece}) 22. exd6 {and Black
can resign.}) 17. exf5 Be5 18. h3 Bh5 19. Nf4 $1 {Simple and decisive,} ({
rather than inviting complications with} 19. g4 Rg8 {.}) 19... Bxf4 20. Bxf4 f6
21. Rae1 Rad8 22. g4 Qc6 23. Qd4 Rd7 24. Bh6 ({Everything loses:} 24. Bh6 Rg8 (
24... Rff7 25. Re8+) (24... Rdf7 25. Bxf8) 25. Qxf6+ Rdg7 26. Re7 {and White
wins the proverbial house - an auspicious beginning for the Four Pawns Attack!}
) 1-0

