{This game is an object lesson on the subject "tempo loss in the opening".
Here my opponent, a solid master, gives me a free tempo in the opening - and I
use that tempo to go straight for the king!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4.
e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. f4 a6 $2 {This is the culprit: the rook's pawn move is too
quiet for the Four Pawns Attack! One could almost say White gets two moves in
a row.} 7. Nf3 c5 ({After the more consistent} 7... c6 8. O-O b5 9. e5 {Black
got a horribly cramped position and soon suffocated in J.Nogueiras-O.Romanishin, Reggio Emilia 1985/86:} Ng4 10. h3 Nh6 11. Be3 Nd7 12. c5 b4 13.
Na4 d5 14. Qd2 Qa5 15. b3 Kh8 16. a3 Qc7 17. axb4 Rd8 18. g4 f5 19. g5 Ng8 20.
Nc3 Bb7 21. Ra5 e6 22. Rfa1 {(a wonderful position for Black!)} Qc8 23. Qa2 Nb8
24. b5 cxb5 25. Nxb5 Nc6 26. Nd6 Qc7 27. Ra4 a5 28. Bd2 {1-0. --- Amusingly
enough, the position after 9 e5 has occurred seven times in the Big Database,
with 5 White wins and 2 draws! In short, mild wing manoeuvres don't exactly
stave off a central juggernaut!}) 8. O-O cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nc6 10. Be3 Ng4 {Now one
sees that Black is playing Pomar-Geller a tempo down, since the a6-pawn has
nothing to say in this position. Given that this game already favoured White,
it's easy to predict even worse here!} 11. Bxg4 Bxd4 12. Bxd4 Bxg4 13. Qd2 (13.
Qxg4 Nxd4 14. Qd1 {, following Pomar, is also good, 0-0 being much more useful
than ...a6, but I decided on a more direct attacking line.}) 13... Nxd4 14.
Qxd4 {The identical position occurred in Uhlmann-Fischer, mentioned in the
previous game, but without 0-0 and ...a6. This makes a huge difference: in
that game Bobby played ...e5 and answered fxe5 with ...Qh4 check (!), which is
not exactly possible here.} Bd7 ({If} 14... e5 {anyway, White gets a winning
attack after} 15. fxe5 dxe5 16. Qxe5 Qb6+ 17. c5 Qxb2 18. Rab1 Qc2 19. Nd5 {
and there is no reasonable defence to mate. Note that losing a single tempo
against the Four Pawns Attack means one might be mated in 20 moves!}) 15. f5 $1
{Another kingside breakthrough, another exclam!} Bc6 16. f6 {The f-pawn won't
stop!} Re8 17. Rad1 e5 18. Qf2 h6 19. Rd3 {A weak black pawn at d6, and weaker
still dark squares around the king - themes do repeat!} Re6 20. Nd5 Kh7 ({On} 
20... Bxd5 21. cxd5 Re8 22. Rh3 h5 ({or} 22... Kh7 23. Rxh6+) 23. Rxh5 {White
gives rooks for mate!}) 21. Rh3 Qf8 ({In view of the threat Rxh6+, Black has
to give up the exchange, as} 21... h5 22. Rxh5+ $1 gxh5 23. Qh4 Qh8 24. Rf5 Kg8
25. Rg5+ Kf8 26. Rxh5 {gives White a winning attack.}) 22. Nc7 Rae8 23. Nxe8
Rxe8 24. Qe3 Rd8 25. g4 $1 {White has just enough room to double rooks on the
h-file.} Bd7 26. Rh4 Be6 27. Rf3 b5 ({Black can prolong the game - but not
change the result - with} 27... h5 28. gxh5 g5 29. Qxg5 Qh6 30. Qg7+ Qxg7+ 31.
fxg7 Kxg7 32. h6+ Kh7 33. b3 {and White easily wins the ending.}) 28. Rfh3 h5
29. Rxh5+ {Black resigns just in time to avoid mate. --- Simply put, given the
sharpness of the opening, Black can't afford to lose a single tempo.} 1-0

