{Black has a tough road in the Martz Variation. I simply can't find a way for
Black to equalize in the main lines. Furthermore, it is very very difficult
for Black to play for a win. Meanwhile, White enjoys attacking chances and
very often positional pressure such as the ubiquitous d6 weakness that Black
must so often suffer. --- The popular 9...Bd7 leads to Accelerated Dragon type
positions where White, because of the double advance of the f-pawn, has
attacking chances to go with a positional squeeze. Improvements are of course
possible in this complex line, but right now the chances are all on White's
side. --- I think Black's best chance in the mainline Martz is the simplifying
9...Bg4 line, especially as seen in Game 8, Martz-Goodman. Black has to defend
extremely accurately, but he may be able to make a draw here. --- The other
lines, as played by Stein and Gligoric, are hopeless nowadays in the one
session era. Perhaps GMs could save those positions back in the day (with the
help of adjournments, seconds and 16 moves an hour), but no one is going to
hold positions with a static weakness at d6 in a sudden death finale! ---
Fischer's 9...Ng4 was killed by Pomar and hasn't come back to life. The ...e5
defences need a lot of White or Tal help to equalize. And the rare defences
seen in Game 15 will probably stay that way.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4.
