1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f4 O-O 6. Nf3 c5 7. Be2 cxd4 8. Nxd4
Nc6 9. Nc2 ({White avoids the main line, the natural development} 9. Be3 {.
This third knight move has always been favoured by GM Bisguier and there is
logic behind it: since White has more space, avoid piece exchanges. However, I
think the dark side of the move is more important. There are two main breaks
by which Black can destroy the Maróczy Bind: ...b5 and ...f5. While the white
knight is centralized on d4, it monitors both of these uprisings. Once it goes
back to c2 Black gets much easier counterplay, as will be seen in the next
note and the following game.}) 9... Bd7 ({A better square for this bishop is
e6, when it will cooperate with the ...b5 pawn break as the following game
shows:} 9... Be6 10. O-O Rc8 11. Be3 a6 12. Rc1 Qa5 13. Kh1 b5 14. cxb5 axb5
15. Bxb5 {a serious mistake;} ({correct is the solid} 15. a3 Bb3 ({if} 15... b4
$2 16. axb4 Nxb4 17. Ra1 {and White wins material}) 16. Qd2 Bxc2 17. Rxc2 b4
18. axb4 Qxb4 19. Bf3 Na5 {with approximate equality}) 15... Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Qxb5
{(Black takes over the initiative and soon wins a pawn: note the strength and
activity of both black bishops)} 17. b3 Ra8 18. Rf2 Rxa2 19. Na1 Rxf2 20. Bxf2
Ra8 21. Nd2 Nd4 22. Nc4 Ra2 23. Bxd4 Qd5 24. Nc2 Rxc2 25. Ne3 Rxc1 {0-1 N.Kopaev-N.Gusev, Lvov 1951.}) 10. O-O Rc8 11. Be3 Na5 12. b3 {White has
consolidated and stands better. The young Fischer clearly did not understand
this position: he finally prepares queenside counterplay (far too late) and
overlooks White's central break. --- Better, though still worse for Black, is
to retreat the knight back to c6.} a6 13. e5 $1 {White takes over the centre.
Black's position is already desperate.} dxe5 14. fxe5 Ne8 15. Nd5 {White's
first big threat is 16 Bb6.} Rc6 {Fischer tries to save the game with
contortionist rook manoeuvres.} 16. Nd4 Rc8 17. Nc2 Rc6 18. Ncb4 Re6 19. Bg4
Rxe5 20. Bb6 Qc8 21. Bxd7 Qxd7 22. Bxa5 e6 23. Nd3 $1 {Bisguier correctly
decides not to cling to material, but instead goes after Bobby's king!} Rh5 ({
A quicker loss comes after} 23... exd5 24. Nxe5 Bxe5 25. Bb4 Bxa1 26. Qxa1 Nd6
27. Qe5 Rd8 28. Bc3 {with a mating attack.}) 24. N3f4 Rf5 25. Bb4 exd5 26. Bxf8
Bxa1 27. Qxa1 Kxf8 28. Qh8+ Ke7 29. Re1+ Kd8 30. Nxd5 {Material is now even,
but there is no answer to White's attack.} Qc6 31. Qf8 Qd7 32. Rd1 {White
threatens 33 Ne3.} Rf6 33. Qxe8+ $1 ({Bisguier concludes with a pretty
combination:} 33. Qxe8+ $1 Qxe8 (33... Kxe8 34. Nxf6+ {is even worse}) 34.
Nxf6+ {and White emerges with an extra rook. Again we see how unfamiliarity
with the Four Pawns Attack can lead to an early exit.}) 1-0

