1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 O-O 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nc6 8. Nc2
d6 9. Be2 {Forty-seven (!) years after his big win over Fischer, Bisguier
takes up the same 9th move position against the well-prepared IM Vladimir
Mezentsev. This time the Maróczy not only fails to bind, it comes unwrapped
right in the opening!} Nd7 {A modern move: where Fischer, following classical
principles, developed a fresh piece to this square, Mezentsev moves an already
developed piece again, on its way to yet a third square! But this wandering
has a point: Black targets both White's e-pawn and the Bind itself, and
shortly eliminates both of those factors.} 10. O-O Nc5 {The black position is
identical to Taylor-Ortiz (note to move 8 in Game 15) but the tempi situation
is very different. In both positions White is to move, but in Taylor-Ortiz
White already had a bishop on d2 and the king was on h1, both useful moves! So
White, two tempi up, was able to sacrifice the e-pawn, hardly possible here. 
(In the Taylor-Ortiz position I was able to play b4 - that won't fly here with
the knight hanging!)} 11. Bf3 {White's last two moves are so natural, it's
hard to find an improvement; but now Black successfully breaks and enjoys at
least equality. In my opinion, Mezentsev's line refutes the Nc2 variation, at
least from the point of view of White getting any advantage out of the opening.
} f5 $1 {I already prefer Black, given the great activity of all Mezentsev's
pieces.} 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Ne3 {A new try: Bisguier had faced this plan before,
and won, but his opponent could take the blame for that result!} ({There
Bisguier played} 13. Nd5 {, Black pushed past the knight with the illogical} e5
{, and the game continued as follows:} ({after the logical} 13... e6 14. Nde3 (
{or} 14. Nc3 Bd3 15. Be2 Bxc2 16. Qxc2 Nd4 17. Qd1 Qb6 18. Kh1 Rad8 {with very
active play for Black}) 14... Bd3 15. Rf2 Rxf4 {Black wins a pawn}) 14. Nce3
Bd3 15. Be2 e4 16. Bxd3 exd3 ({the logical} 16... Nxd3 {gives Black a good
game - but Black continues the impetuous advance of his pawn until it is
finally captured}) 17. Qg4 Rf7 18. Rb1 a5 19. b3 Ne4 20. Qd1 Nc5 21. Bb2 Nd4
22. Qg4 Ne2+ 23. Kh1 Bxb2 24. Rxb2 Qe8 25. Rxe2 $1 {(White kills the advanced
pawn with this fine positional exchange sac)} dxe2 26. Qxe2 Qe4 27. Qb2 Qe6 28.
h3 h5 29. Qf2 Ne4 30. Qh4 Raf8 31. Rf3 Kg7 32. Kg1 Rh8 33. Qe1 Ra8 34. Qa1+ {
(Bisguier manoeuvres adroitly using the whole board, and finally picks up the
full point)} Kh7 35. Qd4 a4 36. b4 Raf8 37. g4 Rh8 38. Kg2 Nf6 39. g5 Ne4 40.
Rf1 Rc8 41. Rh1 Re8 42. Ng4 b5 43. cxb5 Rc8 44. Nge3 Rb7 45. b6 Re8 46. Rc1 Rf8
47. Re1 Rff7 48. Nc4 Rbe7 49. b7 Re8 50. Rxe4 {1-0 A.Bisguier-O.Popovych, US
Open, Lincoln 1969. --- A pretty win for Bisguier, but the only problem - as
I'm sure he was the first to notice - is that Black could have obtained an
excellent game on move 13 simply by kicking back the knight! --- Expecting
some such prepared play in this database age, Bisguier varies, but White's
position is still suspect.}) 13... Nd4 ({Even simpler is} 13... Bd3 14. Bd5+
Kh8 15. Rf2 Nb4 {and Black obtains the two bishops and a generally more active
position.}) 14. Nxf5 Nxf5 15. Re1 Qa5 $6 ({This gives White a chance;} 15...
Bd4+ {and ...e6 should be played, with some advantage to Black.}) 16. Rb1 $2 ({
The text leaves the e-pawn hanging and White should seize this opportunity
with both hands:} 16. g4 $1 Nh4 17. Rxe7 Nxf3+ ({if} 17... Rae8 $2 18. Bd5+ Kh8
19. Rxg7 Kxg7 20. Qd4+ Kh6 21. g5+ Kh5 22. Qd1+ {and mates}) 18. Qxf3 Rae8 19.
Rxg7+ $1 Kxg7 20. Be3 {with attack. Note the recurring theme of powerful
exchange sacrifices to expose Black's king in Taylor-Peters, Bisguier-Popovych,
and this note.}) 16... Bxc3 17. bxc3 e6 {Finally Black forms what Hans Kmoch
called the "duo". Black's centre is impenetrable, the white bishops are
ineffective, and White's pawns are weak.} 18. Re2 Rab8 19. Rb4 Qc7 20. Rbb2 Qg7
21. Rbd2 {White sacrifices to get his pieces in play, which is understandable 
(who wants to defend the doubletons forever?) but probably unsound given
Black's strong knights.} Qxc3 22. Bb2 Qxc4 23. Rxd6 Nxd6 24. Qxd6 Nd7 $4 (24...
Rbd8 25. Qe5 Rd1+ {wins in view of the coming fork on d3.}) 25. Rxe6 $4 {
Back-to-back blunders - one can only suppose time trouble.} (25. Qxd7 {with a
big mate threat is evidently winning for White.}) 25... Qc5+ {Now Black is
just the exchange up.} 26. Qxc5 Nxc5 27. Re7 Rxf4 28. Bd5+ Kf8 29. Rc7 Rf5 {An
excellent pinning combination: Mezentsev easily handles the technical problems.
} 30. Rxc5 b6 31. Rb5 Rd8 32. Ba3+ Kg7 33. Bb2+ ({Not} 33. Bc4 Rd1+ 34. Bf1
Rdxf1# {.}) 33... Kf8 34. Ba3+ Kg7 35. Bb2+ Kh6 36. Bc1+ g5 37. h4 Rdxd5 38.
Bxg5+ Kg6 39. Rb1 Rd4 40. Re1 Rfd5 41. Re6+ Kf5 42. Rf6+ Kg4 43. Kh2 Rd7 44.
Rf3 Ra4 45. a3 Re4 46. Rf6 Rc7 47. Rf2 b5 48. Rf3 Rc2 49. Rg3+ Kf5 50. Rf3+ Ke6
51. Rf6+ Kd5 52. Rh6 Rg4 53. Rxh7 Rcxg2+ 54. Kh1 Rg1+ 55. Kh2 R4g2+ 56. Kh3
Rxg5 $1 {Black emerges with an extra rook. Not a perfect game by any means,
but from the opening point of view, if White can't improve before 11...f5,
then the Nc2 line is effectively out of business.} 0-1

