{These last two games in the chapter feature opening errors by Black and
savage crushes by White. Black must always be aware that, with all those pawns
coming at him, he is on thin ice from the start and simply cannot afford one
careless move.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 c6 $6 ({The
normal and best move for Black here is} 5... O-O {of course - but I sympathize
with Castro here. He is playing the reigning World Champion and doesn't want
to run into any Soviet analysis, so he gets his powerful opponent "out of
book" as early as move five. The only problem with ...c6, which is useful in
many King's Indian lines, is that it is rarely played and has little function
against the Four Pawns Attack; for in our opening, the black c-pawn normally
travels to c5 in one move. Petrosian, not known for his boldness, nonetheless
sees the way to punish his foe - and lashes out with the fourth pawn!}) 6. f4
$1 h5 {Already in trouble, Castro tries to make things interesting or at least
confusing.} ({I followed Petrosian in a recent game, but my opponent didn't go
for Castro's wild try - he just castled, which put his king right where I
wanted it! This game also shows that 5...c6 is too slow, Black doesn't have
any real central counterplay, and he desperately needs it! T.Taylor-M.Robledo,
US Open, Chicago 2006, continued} 6... O-O 7. Nf3 Nbd7 8. e5 Ne8 9. Be3 Qc7 10.
Qd2 a6 11. h4 $1 f5 12. h5 b5 13. hxg6 hxg6 14. cxb5 axb5 15. Bd1 Nb6 16. Bb3+
e6 17. Qf2 Qe7 18. Qg3 Nc7 19. Qxg6 Ncd5 20. Nxd5 exd5 21. Ng5 $1 {1-0 Harsh
treatment! Black resigns in view of the unstoppable 22 Rh8+ and 23 Qh7 mate.})
7. Nf3 Bg4 8. Ng5 {The knight jumps into the weakened g5-square and White is
clearly better.} Qc7 9. e5 {This is Petrosian!} Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Nh7 11. Nxh7 Rxh7
12. Ne4 d5 13. Ng5 Rh8 14. f5 $1 {The standard blow. Petrosian must have been
studying something besides his usual Réti/English/Queen's Gambit.} gxf5 15. e6
$1 {The attack is decisive.} f6 16. Nf7 Rh7 17. O-O dxc4 18. Rxf5 Qb6 19. Be3
c5 20. d5 Nd7 21. Rxh5 Rxh5 22. Qxh5 Qxb2 23. Nd6+ Kd8 24. Qe8+ (24. Qe8+ Kc7
25. Qxd7+ Kb6 26. Nxc4+ Ka6 27. Qa4# {is mate. Petrosian was not known first
and foremost for his attacking skills but he certainly could attack when he
needed to! --- And the moral? Don't play little moves like 5...c6 (or 6...a6,
Game 11) against the Four Pawns Attack, for you will be mated long before such
