1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 {One advantage of playing the 5
Be2 move order is that it masks White's intentions, and so Black might
inadvertently make a "sound developing move" that is unsound against the Four
Pawns Attack!} Nbd7 $6 {Black makes a move which would be right at home in a
Classical King's Indian (if White now played 6 Nf3), but is just misplaced
against the FPA.} 6. f4 O-O 7. Nf3 c5 {Black tries a Benoni set-up, but his
misplaced knight will haunt him.} 8. d5 Ne8 {The normal move in such Benoni
positions is ...e6, but because of the self-blocking knight on d7, here this
would lose a pawn. I think Black would be better off hurling out a doubtful
Benko with 8...b5, rather than passively accept the suffering now inflicted on
him.} 9. O-O a6 10. a4 a5 11. Bd2 Nc7 12. Be1 Nb6 13. h3 e6 {At last, but
Black hardly has any air to breathe.} 14. Bh4 Qd7 15. Qd2 Re8 16. Bd3 h6 17. b3
e5 ({If} 17... exd5 18. exd5 {and Black has only opened the d3-bishop's
diagonal.}) 18. fxe5 dxe5 {Yet giving White a protected passed pawn is no
improvement. We haven't even got to move 20, but it's clear White's advantage
is decisive. Black has no play, while White has the centre (the big protected
passed pawn), the queenside (the hole at b5, the target at a5) and the
kingside (the open f-file is a highway for attack). And all this stemmed from
one "natural" move in the opening, the misplaced 5...Nbd7!} 19. Bf2 {White
manoeuvres adroitly until his pieces overrun the black position.} Bf8 20. Be3
