{The Liz Variation starts with the moves:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4
d6 5. f4 O-O 6. Nf3 c5 7. d5 e6 8. Be2 exd5 9. exd5 {White disobeys the rule
"capture toward the centre" and so avoids a googol of Benoni variations. The
move has its positional logic: the obstructing e-pawn is removed from the
b1-h7 diagonal, so White's light-squared bishop will often find useful
employment later at d3. Also, while White has the same space advantage as in
the Benoni, Black does not have the same queenside pawn majority for
counterplay. The disadvantage of this system is that while White's pawns are
further advanced with concomitant space gain, the pawns are also symmetrically
arranged. Sometimes all the heavy pieces are traded on the e-file with a
subsequent draw. This is why, if White wants to win at all costs, I recommend
the Martz Variation, which has no inherent drawishness. On the other hand, the
Liz Variation can be a relatively safe line of the Four Pawns Attack (if safe
and FPA can be put together!), and White still gets good winning chances in a
slightly more controlled environment. --- This chapter will be concerned with
the basic Liz tabiya reached after the 9th move as stated above - note that I
suggest a different move order from the Martz Variation. The reason is that
here, since White plans d5 anyway, there is no reason to make sure the Maróczy
Bind is possible. In other words, after 1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 g6 3 Nc3 Bg7 4 e4 d6 5
f4 the early 5...c5 (which prevents the Martz) is nothing here since White
just plays 6 d5, heading for the mainline Liz. Furthermore, playing this move
order has two more advantages: if Black plays a deferred Benko, White has
reserved development of his light-squared bishop, which often goes to c4 or b5
in this system - and here can make that jump in one move (see Game 32). The
other advantage is that sometimes Black makes an opening inaccuracy which lets
White play his bishop to d3 in one move (see Game 33). --- If Black plays
accurately, and White aims for it, the Liz tabiya will be reached, and so
after 9 exd5 Black has to form a plan of defence.} -- ({Games 23, 24 and 25
feature the obvious and most popular counters} 9... Re8) ({and} 9... Bf5 {,
where Black seeks counterplay on the open e-file.}) ({Games 26 and 27 feature
the very interesting blockade idea,} 9... Nh5 {, where Black prepares to
exchange his Indian bishop to damage White's pawn structure. Finally, Games 28
and 29 feature unusual 9th moves for Black. --- By the way, in case you're
wondering about the name of the variation, here's a quick explanation. For the
other three main lines in this book, the name of the variation was clear: the
Martz Variation, Knezevic Variation, Keres Variation. In each of these a
specific well-known player either originated or championed the line, and
played it repeatedly with success. So there was no conflict or indecision -
these masters' names had to go with the variation, it was that simple. However,
the line with 9 exd5 had no such champion. A lot of well-known players have
dabbled with the line, but none played it consistently. No strong player
racked up a string of wins with the variation like Martz or Keres, no one
seemed to be the originator and champion of the line like Knezevic. The line
apparently developed almost by accident, and no one paid a lot of attention.
None of the books I consulted on this line gave it a name, so I had to come up
with something! --- At this point I looked over and observed how great my wife
Liz looks in a miniskirt! I considered calling the line the "Miniskirt
Variation" but that seemed to sell it short, so to speak - therefore,
following my muse, I have named this line the Liz Variation!}) *

