{In this chapter I toss out some odds and ends. Let's say you don't want any
kind of main line (whether you're White or Black) - how can you avoid the
basic tabiyas and still get a reasonable game? For White that's not such a
difficult task: This and the next game feature the rare, but playable} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f4 {,} O-O 6. Bd3 {line. --- I must state
right out front that I don't think Bd3 is the best move (either Be2 or Nf3,
depending on your taste or mood, give White good chances for advantage), for
the simple reason that it leaves the central d-pawn undefended. However 6 Bd3
is a terrific surprise weapon (in Game 30 I defeat Susan Polgar in 19 moves!)
and it's no more risky than anything else in the Four Pawns Attack. If Black
knows (or can figure out at the board) the correct response, White can still
count on comfortable equality, with chances for more if Black goes wrong - and
the position is surprisingly difficult for Black to play, even though he can
gain a tempo in the opening. --- However, for Black to deviate from the
accepted lines - with those four menacing pawns staring at him - is a
different story. It's pretty hard to find a sound offbeat line. The most
played of the unusual variations is the delayed Benko Gambit (see Game 32),
but I don't see Black getting anything close to equality - even top players
like Shirov desperately struggle to draw, and White's wins run over 60%. ---
Finally, I will conclude the chapter - and the King's Indian part of this book
- with one more object lesson on the subject of quiet play vs. the Four Pawns
Attack.} *

