{For the final Four Pawns Attack game of this book, I choose a light, rapid
encounter. Don't take this game overly seriously - just enjoy and have some
fun! Chess is not all logic and Fritz crunching - and this opening gives you
the chance, if you choose to take it, to sac like Spielmann!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f4 O-O 6. Nf3 c5 7. d5 Nbd7 $2 {One reason for
holding back the light-squared bishop in the d5 variations is simply that
Black might make a mistake, as here. By delaying ...e6 one move, Black
eliminates his own e-file threats - so White can immediately develop to the
stronger d3-square.} 8. Bd3 e6 9. O-O exd5 10. exd5 Re8 {Not with check!} 11.
Qc2 a6 12. Bd2 Nb6 13. b3 {Black's pieces are shut out of play, while White is
ready to attack.} Bd7 14. Rae1 Qc7 15. f5 $1 {The usual exclam!} Ng4 16. fxg6
hxg6 17. Bxg6 $5 {A Spielmann-style intuitive sac, very very hard to meet over
the board, and virtually impossible in a rapid game.} ({In a slow tournament I
might have preferred the more careful (but less fun!)} 17. Ne4 {with
overwhelming positional advantage.}) 17... Rxe1 ({Or} 17... fxg6 18. Qxg6 Nf6
19. Ne5 $1 Rf8 20. Nxd7 Qxd7 21. Bg5 {with good compensation for the piece.})
18. Bxf7+ Kf8 ({If} 18... Kxf7 19. Rxe1 {and the black king can't escape
White's attack.}) 19. Rxe1 Be8 ({After} 19... Kxf7 20. Ng5+ Kf6 21. Qh7 {White
mates in at most seven; e.g.} Rf8 22. Nce4+ Ke7 23. Qxg7+ Kd8 24. Qxf8+ Be8 25.
Ne6+ Kd7 26. Qg7+ Kc8 27. Qxc7# {.}) 20. Bxe8 {It's all over.} Rxe8 21. Rxe8+
Kxe8 22. Qg6+ Qf7 23. Qxg4 Nd7 24. Qe6+ Qxe6 25. dxe6 Nb8 26. Nd5 {To me, this
is what the Four Pawns Attack is all about. Yes, my sac on g6 might not have
been of "cast iron soundness" to quote Spielmann from his 'Art of Sacrifice',
but it gave White the kind of wonderful attack so rarely seen in this computer
age. --- What can one say of Black's play? --- There is no safety when facing
the Four Pawns, and if you switch the move order (...Nbd7 instead of ...e6)
you can be struggling just to make it to move 30 - and you might not succeed!}
1-0

