wins a game solely because you memorized better - if you win a game without
making a single original move - then what satisfaction will you feel upon
winning? --- This book was already in the works when I saw the Lee-Chapa game,
but it convinced me quite thoroughly that I was on the right track. The only
way to play fun and interesting chess games these days is to play slightly
offbeat, less analyzed and, above all, less fashionable variations. ---
Therefore I offer two lines to beat the Grünfeld, namely the Knezevic: 1 d4
Nf6 2 c4 g6 3 Nc3 d5 4 e3 Bg7 5 Qb3, which is the subject of Chapters 5 and 6;
and the Keres: 1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 g6 3 Nc3 d5 4 Nf3 Bg7 5 e3 0-0 6 cxd5 Nxd5 7 Bc4,
analyzed in Chapters 7 and 8. --- I have a strict criteria for variations I
play these days (and I would not recommend the lines if I did not play them -
one sees my own games sprinkled throughout the book). The lines have to be
sound, and they have to be unfashionable! --- The Knezevic and Keres
Variations hit the Daily Double on the above criteria, so let's have some fun
- enjoy a few novel chess ideas - and forget memorization!} 1-0

