1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. Qb3 e6 6. Qa3 Qe7 {Unlike the
previous game, where Black's 6th move said, "Please, Sir, may I have a draw
now?", this offer to exchange queens says, "I want a draw and I'm willing to
defend for a while - I don't think you can win this with queens off!" --- But
White has no reason not to exchange queens, for the ending favours the first
player. There are quite a few advantages: First, White will get his
dark-squared bishop to the a3-f8 diagonal, where this theoretically "bad"
bishop will become so strong that it will practically have to be exchanged,
leaving Black weak on the dark squares. Next, White has the aggressive
formation in the centre with a bit more space, and while it would rarely be
good for Black to surrender his central toehold with ...dxc4, Black will have
to watch on every move in case cxd5 favours White. Finally, White can operate
on the kingside as well with a possible h4-h5. In short, White has various
positional advantages and board-wide play. All this does not make for a huge
advantage with queens off, but Black must face a very difficult defensive task,
while he has no winning chances whatsoever - meanwhile White can play all
night! --- This brings up an important point, that may be disconcerting to my
readers who have just finished the first part of this book: the King's Indian,
mate him with the Four Pawns Attack part! There White often plays for direct
attack. The lines I recommend against the Grünfeld are more positional in
nature. There are sharp chances for an opening advantage, but sometimes the
advantage can only be realized in the endgame (see Game 50, Taylor-Pomerleano).
While I like straightforward attacking lines, in the Grünfeld Defence these
mainly occur in the Exchange Variation which, as I've mentioned, is booked up
past absurdity. So let's show our versatility and crush our foes positionally!}
7. Qxe7+ ({Best, as if} 7. b3 {Black gets some Grünfeld-style play with} c5 {.}
) 7... Kxe7 8. b3 Rd8 ({If} 8... c5 9. Ba3 b6 10. O-O-O {and Black can hardly
avoid the loss of a pawn.}) 9. Ba3+ {A pretty tremendous "bad" bishop!} Ke8 10.
Rc1 c6 {As I have said before, if Black makes this move in the Grünfeld, he is
accepting his fate to purely defend.} 11. Nf3 a5 12. Be2 ({Sharper is} 12. Bc5
Bf8 (12... Nbd7 {fails to} 13. Bd6 Nb8 14. Bc7 Rd7 15. Be5 {when the bishop is
even more dominant and the weak dark squares on both sides - b6, g5 - call to
White's knights}) 13. Bb6 Rd7 14. c5 Re7 15. Be2 Nbd7 16. Na4 Nxb6 17. Nxb6 Rb8
18. h4 {and Black will have a terrible time defending his weaknesses on both
wings.}) 12... Bf8 ({The trick} 12... a4 13. Nxa4 dxc4 {fails to the simple}
14. Bc5 cxb3 15. axb3 {and the newly created open lines favour White.}) 13.
Bxf8 Kxf8 14. Na4 Nbd7 15. O-O Ke7 16. Rfd1 h6 17. Ne1 $2 {At this point (as
can be seen by the next few moves) White loses the thread, and soon his
advantage, by pointless manoeuvring. Note how he moves Ne1-d3-e5, a square he
could have reached in one!} ({White needs to go over to concrete calculation
here and find a point of attack: this is just the moment for} 17. cxd5 {as all
the recaptures are bad:} Nxd5 ({alternatively,} 17... cxd5 18. Rc7 {when White
dominates and threatens to double on the c-file}) ({or} 17... exd5 18. a3 {and
White can play for a very favourable minority attack, helped on by having the
superior bishop}) 18. e4 Nf4 19. Bf1 {and White takes over the centre. --- In
this logical way White could have increased his opening advantage.}) 17... Rb8
18. Nd3 b6 19. Ne5 Nxe5 20. dxe5 Nd7 21. cxd5 cxd5 22. f4 b5 23. Nc3 b4 24. Na4
Bb7 ({White has succeeded in losing all his advantages, and now the simple} 
24... f6 25. exf6+ Nxf6 26. Nc5 Bd7 {would lead to an approximately equal
French-style position. If White doesn't take on d7, the black bishop will
exchange itself on b5 - in neither case does White have anything.}) 25. Bb5 {
If 25...Bc8 White still has nothing, but Black falls into a positional trap.}
Rdc8 $2 26. Bxd7 $1 {Forced because of the potential fork on b6. Now White has
the better minor piece and the c-file. This time White converts his positional
advantages with no misadventures!} Rxc1 {Forced because of the potential fork
on b6. Now White has the better minor piece AND the c-file. This time White
converts his positional advantages with no misadventures!} 27. Rxc1 Kxd7 28.
Rc5 Bc6 29. Rxa5 Bxa4 30. Rxa4 Rb7 31. Ra6 Kc7 32. Kf2 Kb8 33. g4 Rb5 34. h4
Kb7 35. Ra4 h5 36. gxh5 gxh5 37. Kf3 Kb6 38. Ra8 Rc5 39. Rb8+ Ka5 40. a3 $1 {
Black can't take in view of the fork on b4, so White wins a second pawn, thus
compelling Black's resignation. Yes, White missed a couple of sharp and
accurate moves: 12 Bc5, or 17 cxd5, but even the way he played, White never
had less than a draw - and when Black faltered, White's latent positional
advantages came right back! If you draw this with Black, you earn it!} 1-0

