{The main line (inasmuch as this quite new opening has a main line) where
Black plays 6...Nc6 and 7...Ne7 gives White good chances for positional
advantage. 8 Bd3 combined with e4 (Game 34), 8 Be2 combined with b4 and a
Minority Attack (Game 35), and 8 Bd2 combined with Rc1 and queenside pressure 
(Game 36) all give White at least a small positional advantage. White must
beware of minority attack positions where Black is able to answer b4 with ...b5 and a subsequent knight manoeuvre to c4 - if this is accomplished, Black
will have no worries and might even take over the advantage. However, careful
play in all three lines should give White a pull. I personally think the best
chances for a significant edge lie with the moves 8 Bd3 and 8 Bd2 - Black has
good drawing chances against 8 Be2 if he captures in the centre with his
knight. --- When Black plays for a draw with 6...Bf8 or 6...Qe7, he
essentially limits his ambitions to a half point. White can press for victory
with minimal risk and Black's chances of drawing are probably less than his
chances of losing. --- Finally, the complicated knight and pawns manoeuvre of
Game 39 - where Black tries to block on b4 - should fail against
straightforward development (as opposed to Korchnoi contortions) when White
has good queenside pressure. --- I don't see any line in this chapter that
guarantees Black equality, though there are many "slight plus to White"
positions that can only be evaluated - patiently - in the ending. --- If you
were ready for a fiery Four Pawns Attack, and your opponent crossed you up by
playing the Grünfeld, you have to make a mental adjustment and be ready to
play a 55 move endgame grind!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. Qb3 e6
