{The Keres Variation begins with these moves:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4.
Nf3 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bc4 {. This is the only system in the book 
(both in the King's Indian and Grünfeld part) where, so far as I can see,
there is a clear path to equality for Black: namely the line seen in Game 45,
Najdorf-Korchnoi, where Black counters with} Nxc3 8. bxc3 c5 9. O-O Qc7 {.
Korchnoi's line leads to a dynamically equal (but not drawish) position. ---
Therefore I suggest the Knezevic Variation for full strength opening advantage
against the Grünfeld, and the Keres line for surprise value. Given the line's
rarity in present day play, most Grünfeld players (who have been staying up
nights memorizing the Exchange Variation) will be surprised - but even if not,
White can obtain a solid, even position - and just play chess! --- Keres
himself did not claim White got any advantage: he called his variation "a
modest system" that reached a position "which is not without problems for both
sides". His main reason for playing his line was to avoid booked-up variations
- as he said in 1972 of the then popular Taimanov variation (4 Bg5): "this has
been played too much in recent months to be successful." --- Despite these
"modest" goals, one should note that Keres had a lifetime score of four wins
and two draws with his line, which is a result we all could envy!} *

