{This is an extremely heavyweight encounter between two players who were, at
the time, among the very best in the world.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4.
Nc3 d5 5. e3 O-O 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bc4 {The inaugural game with this system - so
some might wonder why I call it the Keres System rather than Rubinstein.
However, Rubinstein only played it twice, while Keres played the system
throughout his career with great success.} Nxc3 {The most popular and, in my
opinion, the best move. Grünfeld himself played this way. Black meets the
attack on his knight without loss of time, and immediately follows with the
standard counter ...c5 (a move that was so difficult for Black to achieve in
the Knezevic Variation).} (7... Nb6 {and other deviations from this main line
will be covered in Chapter 8.}) 8. bxc3 c5 9. O-O {The basic Keres tabiya has
been reached. Here Black has achieved the standard Grünfeld ...c5 break, but
White's centre is more solid than in Exchange Variation lines, as the e-pawn
has stopped at e3 (though this blocks White's dark-squared bishop). Sometimes
Black tries to attack the d-pawn again with ...e5, but must then risk the
formation of a protected passed pawn for White, as the first player can follow
with d5 and c4. --- Another interesting feature of the position is that while
White's dark-squared bishop is blocked from a "normal" development on the
c1-h6 diagonal, the piece often finds a home on a3, where under the right
circumstances it can become very strong, bearing down on Black's king position.
} Nc6 ({Best and most forceful here is} 9... Qc7 {, with the threat of 10...
cxd4, attacking White's bishop on c4. Grünfeld played this way against
Rubinstein, but continued inaccurately, soon had a lost position, and was only
saved by a chess miracle:} 10. Qe2 Nd7 {(too slow and passive)} ({correct is
the much more active} 10... Bg4 {which tends to overload the white queen - see
the critical Najdorf-Korchnoi encounter, Game 45, for full analysis}) 11. e4 {
(White takes over the centre, which would be impossible with the black bishop
on g4)} Nb6 12. Bb3 Bg4 13. Be3 c4 ({if Black tries to increase the pressure
on the centre with} 13... Rad8 {,} 14. Rad1 {is of course playable,} ({but
White also has the interesting gambit} 14. h3 $5 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 cxd4 16. cxd4
Bxd4 17. Rac1 Qb8 ({or if} 17... Qe5 18. Bh6 {wins the exchange}) 18. Bg5 {
with a good attack for the pawn})) 14. Bc2 e5 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 exd4 17.
cxd4 Rad8 18. Rfd1 {(White's centre is much more powerful than Black's
queenside pawn majority)} Qd7 19. Rab1 Nc8 20. a4 Ne7 21. Bg5 f6 22. Bc1 Nc6
23. d5 Ne5 24. Qc3 g5 25. f4 {(White should not have many problems winning
this)} gxf4 26. Bxf4 Rc8 27. Bxe5 fxe5 28. Rb4 Qc7 29. d6 Qc5+ 30. Kh1 Rf2 31.
d7 Rd8 32. Rxc4 Qf8 33. Bd3 Bf6 34. Rc8 Qg7 {. From this point onward,
Rubinstein starts playing (in complete contrast to his sharp and accurate play
so far) weakly and passively, and finally lets the position deteriorate into a
draw. White can decide the game most simply right now:} 35. Bc4+ ({instead,
the game continued} 35. Bf1 $2 Qg5 36. Qc4+ Kg7 37. Qd3 Be7 38. Kg1 Rff8 39.
Rc7 b6 40. Rxa7 Bc5+ 41. Kh1 Be3 42. Rc7 Rf3 43. Be2 Rf2 44. Rg1 Bd4 45. Kh2 h5
46. Kh1 Rf7 47. Rf1 Rfxd7 48. Rxd7+ Rxd7 49. Qf3 Bc5 50. Bb5 Rc7 51. Bc4 h4 52.
Ba2 Kh7 53. Bd5 Kg7 54. Qd1 Bd4 55. Qf3 Qf4 56. Qd1 Qg5 57. Qb1 Qd2 58. a5 $4 (
{even now Rubinstein could win with} 58. Qb5 Kh7 ({if} 58... Rc1 $2 59. Qd7+ {
and mates}) 59. Bc4 {and White should be able to set up a winning attack 
(while keeping his extra pawn) now that his bishop is activated - but he
evidently had a blind spot regarding this simple idea and soon has to force
