{This game is the critical line of the whole Keres Variation. In this battle
between two world class players, Black succeeds in clearly equalizing the game.
There may be nothing much for White here, but I found an interesting game
where White tried to improve with 11 Bd5 and did indeed get a small edge -
though I also found a key improvement for Black which might send the position
back to equal-land! Black players should pay close attention to the "move
order" note to Black's 11th move, which looks like a good (but so far rarely
tried) system of defence, in which Black gives up the two bishops to double
White's kingside pawns.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 5. e3 O-O 6.
cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bc4 Nxc3 8. bxc3 c5 9. O-O Qc7 10. Qe2 Bg4 11. Ba3 {The normal
move, but Korchnoi equalizes with ease; and there is the alternate idea given
in the next note that might also equalize for Black.} ({Given the situation,
White might well look for an improvement on this move, and the most promising
seems to be} 11. Bd5 {.} -- ({The idea is that the bishop escapes the black
queen's veiled attack, while moving to a useful diagonal where it attacks b7
and defends f3. If Black chases the bishop with ...e6 and ...f5, he incurs
some weaknesses in his position. The following game shows White obtain a
slight edge:} 11... Nd7 12. h3 Nf6 13. Bxb7 Qxb7 14. hxg4 Nxg4 15. Ba3 cxd4 16.
cxd4 Nf6 17. Rab1 Qe4 {and now instead of the retreat} 18. Nd2 {which led to a
draw in A.Niemela-M.Myllyniemi, Helsinki 1992,} ({White should increase his
advantage with the sharp} 18. Qa6 $1 {targeting a7 and e7.})) ({Also, after} 
11... e6 12. Be4 f5 {(this weakens Black's position)} ({for the alternative} 
12... Nd7 {see the next note}) 13. Bc2 cxd4 14. cxd4 Bxf3 15. gxf3 e5 16. Ba3
Rd8 17. Bb3+ Kh8 18. Rac1 {White is also slightly better as the active bishops
outweigh the doubled pawns - check out the open diagonals for the white
bishops (which will not be seen in the Nguyen game given in the note to
Black's 11th move).})) ({This may seem convincing, but alas - it's my duty as
this book's author to find the best move for both sides, or the best plan, and
when I looked at the above variations I remembered the ...b5 idea that almost
surfaced in Ivkov-Korchnoi (note to Game 44). I wondered where that might come
in - and soon found a good opportunity for counterplay: after} 11. Bd5 e6 12.
Be4 {as above, Black should not weaken his position with} f5 {,} ({but rather
develop with my (so far untried) suggestion} 12... Nd7 $1 {. The idea is that
after} 13. Ba3 Rab8 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 b5 $1 {Black develops excellent
queenside counterplay, which in my opinion fully equalizes the game. --- I
felt good after finding this idea (it's always good when you feel like you've
uncovered the truth of a position), but then I suddenly remembered I was
supposed to be beating the Grünfeld! Unfortunately I haven't been able to
refute either myself or Korchnoi in this game, so the verdict still stands -
at the time of this writing - as equal. --- But as I said in the beginning of
the chapter, Keres didn't play this variation to force some sharp theoretical
edge: he played it to avoid theory while obtaining a rich middlegame, and this
is what we have here.})) 11... Nd7 {Black can also play to double White's
f-pawns, but one has to be careful about the move order.} (11... Bxf3 $6 {is
incorrect as White can surprisingly take with the queen! Keres shows how this
is done:} 12. Qxf3 $1 cxd4 {(Black might have thought he had something,
discovering an attack on White's bishop, but Keres was ready with...)} 13. Bd5
$1 {(White's point! - by threatening the b-pawn and the a8-rook, White gains
time to recapture on d4; the upshot is that White gets the two bishops and
queenside pressure at no cost)} Nc6 14. cxd4 Qd7 15. Rfc1 Rac8 16. h4 Bf6 17.
h5 Rfd8 18. Be4 Rc7 {. So far P.Keres-L.Pachman, Marianske Lazne 1965, but now
the great Estonian threw away most of his advantage with the simplifying} 19.
Bxc6 $2 {and the game was eventually drawn.} ({Instead White should increase
his pressure to decisive proportions with} 19. Rc5 Rdc8 20. Rac1 {and Black
will hardly be able to hold.})) ({Black's idea, to double White's pawns, is
correct if played in the reverse move order:} 11... cxd4 $1 12. cxd4 {(White
must recapture - there are no tricks here)} Bxf3 13. gxf3 {(forced)} Nc6 14.
Rac1 Qa5 15. Bb2 e6 16. Kh1 Rfd8 17. Rg1 Rac8 18. f4 Ne7 {with about an even
game in D.Blair-D.Nguyen, New Hampshire 2000. White has the two bishops, but
also must live with the long-term structural weakness of the doubled pawn
complex. The position reminds me of some lines of the Chigorin Defence. I'd
say it's dynamically equal. --- If my assessment is correct, then that means
Black has two ways of equalizing against this system!}) 12. Rac1 Qa5 13. Bb2
Rac8 {It's clear that Black has active Grünfeld play, and equally clear that
White has no advantage. Najdorf accepts reality and steers the game toward a
draw.} 14. a3 (14. h3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 b5 16. Bd3 Nb6 {looks slightly better for
Black, as the limited bishop on b2 is about to come under attack from Black's
strong knight.}) 14... cxd4 {Normally I disapprove of this move in the Keres
system, as it frequently serves only to free White's dark-squared bishop. Here,
however, Black is so well developed that the now open c-file becomes a
dangerous avenue of counterplay for Black. Najdorf must exchange everything on
it and accept equality.} 15. cxd4 Nb6 16. Bb3 Bd7 17. Rxc8 Rxc8 18. Rc1 (18.
Ne5 $5 Bxe5 19. dxe5 Bb5 $6 {(but Black doesn't have to "bite")} ({correct is} 
19... Ba4 $1 {(which forces the exchange of bishops because of the latent
threat ...Rc2 - note how well Black uses the c-file!) and it's clear that
Black has active queenside play}) 20. Qf3 {is an interesting attacking idea.})
18... Rxc1+ 19. Bxc1 e6 20. Qe1 Qxe1+ 21. Nxe1 Bb5 {A model game from Black's
point of view. As far as I can see from the main game and key notes, Black can
equalize against the Keres Variation.} 1/2-1/2

