1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bc4 Nxc3 8.
bxc3 c5 9. O-O {We have already seen (Korchnoi and Grünfeld explained it all
to us) that 9...Qc7 is the best move for Black, often gaining a vital tempo on
the unprotected bishop on c4, and preparing immediate queenside activity. But
who studies this? Because of the rarity of the opening, to many people this
position is as new as it was to Alekhine in 1922! And a very logical move
would be to develop a minor piece to attack the centre - which explains why
Alekhine's 9...Nc6 is played nearly as often as Grünfeld's more accurate 9...
Qc7, even to the present day. So here is one more instructive game featuring
Alekhine's old move.} Nc6 10. Ba3 cxd4 {Ekutimishvili probably didn't realize
he was making the same mistake Alekhine made in 1922! This exchange opens the
a3-f8 diagonal for White's dark-squared bishop.} ({As I said before, Black
should sac with} 10... b6 {and hope for the best - at least White would have
to break up his centre to get the pawn.}) 11. cxd4 Bg4 ({Alekhine played} 11...
a6 {here; White is better regardless, given his solid centre and active
bishops.}) 12. Rb1 Na5 13. Bd3 Rc8 14. Qe2 Re8 15. Rfd1 a6 16. h3 Bd7 ({Worse
is} 16... Bxf3 17. Qxf3 {and the two bishops just add to White's advantages.})
17. Bb4 {Pointless.} ({Since the pawns have been exchanged in the centre,
Keres should return to his set-up vs. Malich (Game 44) and play} 17. Bb2 {and
e4 with solid plus.}) 17... Ba4 18. Rdc1 Rxc1+ 19. Rxc1 Nc6 20. Bc3 e5 $1 {
White's last few aimless moves have allowed this break, and White has to
exchange, being unable to push past - but one notes, if the white e-pawn were
already on e4 (as recommended above) White could now play d5 with advantage.}
21. dxe5 Nxe5 22. Bxe5 Bxe5 23. Be4 Qd7 (23... Bh2+ {fails to a clever tactic:}
24. Nxh2 Rxe4 25. Qb2 h5 26. Qxb7 {and White suddenly has a decisive attack -
the weak dark squares, caused by the unsound exchange of the fianchettoed
bishop, are fatal.}) 24. Qc4 ({Best is} 24. Nxe5 Rxe5 25. Bf3 {and White
retains a minimal advantage.}) 24... b5 25. Qb4 Bd6 $2 {A mistake, allowing
White to centralize and recover the advantage.} ({Correct is} 25... Bg7 {
(Black can play this as the skewer fails to the pin:} 26. Bc6 Qc7 $1 {) when
Black threatens 26...a5 and stands better, due to his two bishops and
queenside pawn majority.}) 26. Qd4 b4 27. Bd5 {White is better again, with
powerfully centralized pieces and, soon, a kingside attack.} Qe7 28. h4 $1 h6
29. h5 g5 30. Qd3 $1 {A neat tactic: White threatens Qg6+ and so picks up a
pawn on the other side of the board.} Kg7 31. Qxa6 Bd7 32. Rd1 g4 33. Bxf7 $2 {
A completely unnecessary sacrifice.} (33. Bb3 {is good enough, maintaining the
extra pawn.}) 33... gxf3 $2 {Black is bamboozled!} ({Correct is} 33... Kxf7 34.
Rxd6 (34. Qxd6 Qxd6 35. Rxd6 Ke7 {is better for Black}) 34... gxf3 35. Qd3 Be6
36. Qh7+ Kf8 {and White should probably take the perpetual, as the ending
reached after} 37. Qxh6+ Qg7 38. Qxg7+ (38. Rxe6 $4 Rxe6 {wins for Black})
38... Kxg7 39. Rb6 Bxa2 40. Rxb4 fxg2 {is marginally better for Black.}) 34.
Qxd6 {Now White is just winning.} Qxf7 35. Qxd7 Qxd7 36. Rxd7+ Kf6 37. gxf3 Ra8
38. Rb7 Ra4 39. Kg2 Kg5 40. Rb5+ Kh4 41. f4 Kg4 42. Rb6 Kxh5 43. Kg3 Rxa2 44.
Rxb4 {A messy game, but instructive for the opening and early middlegame.
White obtained his ideal position, but then failed to occupy the centre and so
gave Black counterplay. Even though Black stood well at one point, his opening
(with 9...Nc6) cannot be recommended.} 1-0

