{For the sake of completeness, in the last two games of this chapter I will
look at lines where Black does not play the natural Grünfeld move 8...c5.
These lines have an artificial aspect, and often lose time - Black usually
finds out he can't do without ...c5 after all, and plays it with a delay.
White should be prepared for this type of defence, since Black may be
unfamiliar with the Keres line and will seek to avoid "book" - but the famous
Najdorf-Korchnoi game really is the way to go.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4.
Nf3 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bc4 Nxc3 8. bxc3 b6 9. O-O ({Since 8...b6 is
so slow, I think White can attack immediately with h4, as the American
correspondence World Champion, Hans Berliner, liked to do in similar positions.
The following game shows White immediately take over the advantage, and even
win a pawn (though he self-destructs later):} 9. h4 Nc6 10. Ng5 ({in my opinion
} 10. h5 $1 {is even stronger: White opens a kingside file by force}) 10... Bf6
11. Qf3 Bb7 12. Qh3 Na5 13. h5 Bc8 14. Ne6 g5 15. Nxd8 Bxh3 16. Bxf7+ Kh8 17.
Rxh3 Raxd8 18. Be6 {(White has emerged from the complications with an extra
pawn)} c5 19. Bd2 h6 20. Rf3 $6 ({White loses the thread:} 20. Rb1 {with a
queenside attack, while keeping the white king in the centre where it is safe,
would probably have brought home the full point - instead, a strange reversal
occurs}) 20... Kg7 21. a4 Rd6 22. Ba2 Rfd8 23. d5 $2 c4 24. e4 e6 25. Re3 Be5
26. O-O-O exd5 27. exd5 Rxd5 28. Ree1 Nb3+ 29. Bxb3 {0-1 S.Greanias-I.Gurevich,
World Open, Philadelphia 1990.}) 9... Nc6 10. Qe2 Na5 11. Bd3 c5 {Black plays ...c5 after all, but of course the loss of time favours White, and the knight
on a5 is not exactly an ornament of Black's position!} 12. Ba3 Qc7 13. Rac1 Bb7
14. e4 e6 15. Qe3 Rfd8 16. Rfd1 Rac8 17. Bb2 Qc6 18. Qe2 cxd4 {The same
unnecessary exchange as in Keres-Malich (Game 44). Black should wait and see
what White can do.} 19. cxd4 Qa4 20. Ba1 Qa3 21. Rb1 Rc7 22. h3 Qd6 23. Bb2
Rdc8 24. Ne5 Qe7 25. Ng4 Rd8 {White has a nice plus, typical of the variation,
but how to utilize it?} 26. e5 $6 {I don't like this move which gives d5 to
the black pieces.} ({The best way to increase White's advantage is} 26. Qe3 {
, as seen in a similar position in Keres-Malich. The queen eyes the weak dark
squares around the black king, with a possible d5-break on the agenda (to
destroy the g7-bishop that defends those squares). In this case Black would
find it very difficult to defend.}) 26... Bd5 27. Bc1 h5 28. Ne3 Ba8 29. Bb2
Qh4 30. Rbc1 Nc6 {My guess is the game went into time pressure here for both
players.} 31. d5 Nd4 $2 {If GM Tukmakov had had time, I'm sure he would have
seen 31 d5 was bluff.} ({Correct is} 31... exd5 32. e6 {(evidently the idea -
on anything else Black just has an extra pawn)} fxe6 33. Bxg6 Bxb2 34. Qxb2 d4
35. Nc4 Rg7 {and Black is winning.}) 32. Bxd4 Rxc1 33. Rxc1 Qxd4 34. dxe6 $1
Qxe5 {The bluff worked!} ({Now White is much better, as Black's king position
is destroyed, and the white bishop is immune:} 34... Qxd3 $2 35. Qxd3 Rxd3 36.
e7 {and queens.}) 35. exf7+ Kxf7 36. Bc4+ $2 ({White misses a win with} 36. Qc2
Qg5 37. Qb3+ {and White has a decisive attack with the rook coming to c7.})
36... Kf8 37. Qc2 Qg5 38. Qb3 {The game ends here with a roughly even position
- but the score is 0-1, so presumably Black won on time; the last few moves
certainly point to extreme time trouble.} 0-1

