{What is White aiming for in the mainline Keres? The reader should take
careful note of three positions: after 12 Rc1 in Game 43, Rubinstein-Alekhine;
after 18 cxd4 in Game 44, Keres-Malich; and after 11 cxd4 in Game 46,
Keres-Ekutimishvili. All these positions have two factors in common: Black has
already captured with ...cxd4, so there is no pressure on White's centre, and
both White's bishops are active. If you can get this sort of position, you can
be happy! Usually Keres would win such games with a kingside attack, often
employing moves like h4-h5 and Qe3, targeting the weak dark squares around the
black king. --- The only problem with this rosy scenario is that these
"perfect" positions cannot be forced! The proverbial fly in the ointment is
the terrible Mr. Korchnoi himself, who figured out how to equalize against the
Keres system back in 1971 (Najdorf-Korchnoi, Game 45), and I haven't been able
to find any worthwhile improvement (though I did find an alternate equalizing
plan - see the "move order note" at move 11). The critical position in
Najdorf-Korchnoi is after 11...Nd7. Note the black knight developed in one
move to an excellent square where it defends the c5-pawn and so blocks White's
dark-squared bishop. Furthermore, Black has no intention of taking on c4 until
he himself is doubled on the c-file - while White is hampered by his own pawn
at c3. Try as I might, I can't find any plus for White here. --- What should
you do if your opponent knows how to play this line? One should note that the
ending reached where Najdorf and Korchnoi agreed a draw is equal but by no
means dead, given the unbalanced pawn structure. One could certainly play this
on and try to outplay your opponent. However, I must honestly admit that in
the future I will only be employing the Keres Variation on rare occasions, for
surprise value, now that I know Black can reach equality following a fairly
clear sequence. --- I repeat that Keres himself never claimed his line gave
White any advantage; he used it just to get out of book and get into a rich
middlegame. If you look at it that way, you can have fun with this - and
besides, who knows Najdorf-Korchnoi, Hastings 1971/72 anyway? --- One final
note: The last two games of this chapter feature lines that the White player
will be happy to meet! If Black delays the standard Grünfeld counterplay with ...c5, first of all White gains time, and second, Black will soon find he has
no play at all until he comes up with ...c5 after all! I think that in Game 47,
Golz-Tukmakov, White can practically overrun Black with the rare but strong 9
h4!, while even the solid game line gives White a pleasant plus. --- Likewise
in Game 48, Nei-Gurgenidze, White can simply occupy the centre and secure a
solid advantage where Black can only hope to draw.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bc4 Nxc3 8. bxc3 c5 (8... b6 {- Game 47
}) (8... Nc6 {- Game 48}) 9. O-O Qc7 (9... Nc6 10. Ba3 cxd4 11. cxd4 a6 {-
Game 43} (11... Bg4 {- Game 46})) 10. Qe2 -- (10... b6 {- Game 44}) (10... Bg4
{- Game 45}) *

