line (particularly Game 45, Najdorf-Korchnoi) is Black's best choice! --- The
White player interested in "beating the Grünfeld", however, should be prepared
for all lines, so to begin with I consider the "best of the rest", namely the
retreat 7...Nb6 (Games 49-51), while touching on inferior 7th moves like 7...c6 - you all know my opinion of this kind of move in the Grünfeld! - and the
other, also doubtful protections, ...e6 and ...Be6. --- Finally, I will wrap
up the book with a quick look at the Schlechter Slav. Depending on how you
look at it, this might not be a Grünfeld at all, but as it can be reached by
transposition - and I have had more than one opponent prefer this passive Slav
line to the Grünfeld, when they guess I have a prepared variation ready - then
the White player must in turn be prepared for this eventuality. --- The good
news is there is not a lot of theory to learn: White scores a high winning
percentage against the Schlechter Slav with easy and natural moves. And as I
say for the millionth time, the fianchettoed dark-squared bishop does not go
well with the c6/d5 pawn formation, as Black needs the ...c5-break to activate
his bishop.} *

