gxf4 37. Nxb7 {Portisch's clean exchange up play reminds me of Alekhine-Yates,
Game 2.} Qb8 38. Nd6 Re7 39. Qxf5 Nh6 40. Qxf4 Qxb4 41. Rxc6 Qb3 42. Rc8+ Ng8
43. Rf1 Qe6 44. Qf5 ({Black resigns, for if} 44. Qf5 Qxf5 45. Nxf5 Rxe5 46. Nd6
{the smothered mate threat wins Black's remaining rook. --- It's quite hard
for Black to get along in the Grünfeld without the counterattacking ...c5.
White can't prevent this move, but Black can choose not to play it - in which
case the White player should look for a big plus early! And notice again how
themes repeat from different variations, as here with the Nc5-e6 idea.}) 1-0

