{The last two games of the book feature the Schlechter Slav, or Slav/Grünfeld,
which is a strange hybrid indeed! I can't resist quoting Chris Ward from his
excellent recent book, 'Play the Queen's Gambit': "We are entering what is
commonly referred to as the Slav Grünfeld, which in itself is almost a
contradiction of terms, as in their purest forms you probably couldn't find
two more opposite defences. The former bolsters the centre and doesn't usually
budge an inch, whilst the second typically donates the opponent a big centre
only to strike back at it later!" --- I couldn't have said it better myself,
and now I don't have to!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Nf3 Nc6
6. e3 g6 7. Qb3 Bg7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O {The Schlechter Slav is most often
reached through the Slav order, as here, but could be reached via the Grünfeld
as follows: 1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 g6 3 Nc3 d5 4 Nf3 Bg7 5 e3 c6 6 cxd5 (to deprive
Black forever of the ...c5-break) 6...cxd5 7 Qb3 Nc6 8 Bd3 0-0 9 0-0 and the
game position has been reached. --- Black now has two positional problems: one
is how to develop his queen's bishop, and two is how to make his passive
king's bishop useful! The first is fairly simple to solve, albeit at the cost
of a queenside weakness (see White's 11th move), but the second remains
intransigent until Black creates central pawn weaknesses with 17...e5.} b6 ({
Another straightforward try is} 9... Rb8 {, but the rook move means that Black
will be a tempo behind in the race to the only open file; e.g.} 10. Bd2 Bf5 11.
Bxf5 gxf5 12. Rac1 e6 13. Na4 Ne4 14. Nc5 Qe7 15. Nd3 Rfc8 16. Rc2 Rc7 17. Rfc1
Rbc8 18. Be1 Bh6 19. g3 Bf8 20. Qa4 Qe8 21. Nfe5 Nxe5 22. Qxe8 Rxc2 23. Nxe5
Rxe8 24. Rxc2 Bd6 {½-½ D.Marovic-W.Uhlmann, Zagreb 1965. So the higher
rated player gets another courtesy draw, but actually the c-file gives White a
considerable edge: after} 25. Nd3 Re7 26. f3 Ng5 27. Kf2 f6 ({if} 27... Rc7 $2
28. Rxc7 Bxc7 29. h4 {wins a piece}) 28. Bb4 Bxb4 29. Nxb4 {White will have
annoying pressure for a long time to come.}) 10. Bd2 Bg4 ({Alternatively Black
can simply fianchetto the bishop, when the holes at c6 and a6 are covered,
albeit at the cost of two inactive bishops! After} 10... Bb7 11. Rac1 Na5 {,
instead of the unnecessary retreat} 12. Qd1 {of S.Barrio Garcia-J.Rodriguez
Uria, Asturias 2000,} ({White should have played the active} 12. Qa4 {with
lasting pressure.})) 11. Qa4 $1 {White strikes at the weak squares.} Bxf3 ({If
Black plays the natural} 11... Rc8 {, then White is clearly better after} 12.
Ba6 Rc7 13. Nb5 Rd7 14. Rfc1 {.}) 12. Qxc6 Bg4 13. Rac1 Bd7 14. Qb7 Rb8 15. Qa6
({The queen slips out with continued pressure - not of course} 15. Qxa7 Ra8 16.
Qb7 Rb8 {and Black makes a draw.}) 15... Ra8 ({If} 15... Rc8 16. Nb5 {renews
the threat to a7.}) 16. Rc2 Qb8 17. h3 e5 {Black lashes out, at the cost of
weakening the d-pawn - but on quiet moves White increases the pressure
routinely via Rfc1 and Nb5. Notice that Black has no other way of activating
his dark-squared bishop, for in this Slav Exchange pawn formation, there is no
c-pawn to strike at White's centre!} 18. Nb5 Bxb5 (18... e4 19. Be2 {would be
a great reversed French, when White has all the c-file play, and the "bad
French bishop" here comes out via b4.}) 19. Bxb5 exd4 20. Bc6 dxe3 21. Bxe3 Qc7
22. Rfc1 Rad8 23. Bxd5 Qe5 24. Bf3 {The tactical flurry has ended, and now we
can see the transition of advantages: Black has freed his game, but White has
the two bishops in an open position and continuing pressure on a7. Black still
faces an uphill struggle, with no equalization in sight.} Nd5 (24... Rd7 {,
holding material equality, would be more tenacious.}) 25. Bxd5 Rxd5 26. Qxa7 {
Black doesn't have enough counterplay to get the pawn back.} Rfd8 27. Rc8 Qxb2
28. Rxd8+ Rxd8 29. Qxb6 Ra8 30. a4 $1 {White is able to defend the a-pawn by
tactical means; once this pawn is secured, White's advantage is decisive.} Qa3
({Both pawn captures fail:} 30... Rxa4 31. Rc8+ Bf8 32. Qxb2 {wins the queen,})
({while} 30... Qxb6 31. Bxb6 Rxa4 32. Rc8+ Bf8 33. Bc5 {wins a piece.}) 31. Rc4
$1 Be5 ({The vital passed pawn still cannot be taken:} 31... Rxa4 32. Rc8+ Bf8
{and now} 33. Bc1 $1 {destroys the coordination of Black's forces} ({but not} 
33. Bh6 $2 {when} Qa1+ 34. Kh2 Ra8 {defends}) 33... Qe7 ({Black has to leave
the a-file, for if} 33... Qa1 34. Qd8 Qg7 35. Bb2 f6 36. Rc7 Qh6 37. Qd5+ Kh8
38. Bxf6+ {mates}) 34. Bh6 {wins a piece.}) 32. g3 h5 ({Again taking the pawn
allows a winning attack:} 32... Rxa4 33. Rc8+ Kg7 34. Qd8 {and Black has to
start tossing pieces to stop the mate on h8.}) 33. Qc6 {White has firmly
secured the pawn and has a decisive advantage. A few more time pressure 
(unrecorded) moves were played, but Black could find no defence and resigned
soon. --- This is one of those lines where a strong GM (see the
Marovic-Uhlmann game given in the notes) might make a draw after a certain
amount of suffering, but Black has very little activity and barely any winning
chances. I don't like the combination of king's fianchetto and ...c6! Note how
Black had to weaken his centre pawns with 17...e5 to get any play.} 1-0

