{The 7...Nb6, 8...c5 line seen in Games 49 and 50 is certainly playable, but
White gets a persistent edge. Basically Black can suffer either in the
middlegame (Game 49) or the endgame (Game 50). In my opinion the latter offers
Black the best drawing chances, but it's a thankless chore. Meanwhile White
has all the chances, and risks very little. --- The lines where Black plays in
Grünfeld style and then avoids ...c5 (Game 51) are inferior as usual. White
can usually get a nice positional grind game, as Portisch showed. --- The last
two games simply show that the Slav/Grünfeld marriage is not a match made in
heaven! For some reason the line is fairly popular, but White has any number
of ways to get a solid edge - Black has essentially eliminated his own
counterplay by stopping his c-pawn at c6! --- Finally, just because World
Champions have for years played a certain opening move doesn't mean said
opening move is any good!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. e3 O-O (
